    <h1>What is the Bearing Witness Archive?</h1>
    <p>"Bearing Witness" is an online archive of projects completed by law students for seminars at Allard School of Law (formerly UBC Faculty of Law) on Aboriginal and Treaty Rights and Penal Policy over the years 1999–2023. In these seminars students were offered the opportunity, as an alternative to the traditional written seminar paper, to present their ideas, perspectives, critiques and conclusions regarding the issues of Indigenous and Prisoners' Rights through art and mixed media.</p>
    <p>These presentations have taken many forms, including Indigenous blankets, ceremonial objects, weavings, embroidered tapestries, photo essays, documentary videos, paintings, collages, sculptures, lithographs, poetry, illustrated stories, ceramics, beading, jewellery, choreographed dances, original songs and music, pictorial and textual reviews and annotations to historical and modern day treaties and even board games. In each case students provided an explanatory accompanying essay or artist statement linking their work to the themes of the seminars.</p>
    <p>The archive presently contains over 120 projects. To situate the projects within the broader legal and historical context of the seminars, each work is accompanied by my curatorial commentary.</p>

    <h2>Storytelling, Indigenous Methodologies, and Reconciliation</h2>
    <p>This body of work is a remarkable testament — hence "Bearing Witness" — to the intellectual and artistic imagination of students at the Law School. It is my hope that the archive will make a contribution to innovative legal teaching and learning. In the last number of years, scholars, particularly Indigenous scholars, have embraced the importance of storytelling as a methodology, both in the form of oral histories and other forms of verbal and visual communication in understanding the history and experiences of Indigenous peoples in Canada and addressing and redressing the legacies of colonialism. The archive also celebrates Indigenous forms of communication which feature artistic ceremonial regalia as performative law.</p>
    <p>The work demonstrates the power of art in animating discussion on the issues of the rights of Indigenous Peoples and Prisoners. As many of the presentations illustrate, these issues are deeply intersected with dispossession, displacement and the overrepresentation, indeed mass incarceration, of Indigenous peoples in Canadian prisons, one of the many continuing legacies of colonialism. Many projects address the critical issue of Reconciliation of Indigenous and non-Indigenous Canadians in a mutually respectful long-term relationship and what the Supreme Court of Canada has characterized as "the grand purpose of s. 35 of the Constitution Act 1982." In this way I hope the archive makes an important contribution to the role in the reconciliation process of the legal profession, and particularly the Law School, in accordance with the recommendations and Calls to Action of the Final Report of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission.</p>

    <h2>The West Coast Context</h2>
    <p>On the West Coast of Canada we have become accustomed to Indigenous art forms as powerful and visually evocative communicators. On arrival at Vancouver International Airport new and returning travelers to Canadian soil are met with a visual feast of Indigenous totem poles, masks, carved panels and tapestries in the architectural construction of an Indigenous landscape. However, it is a pristine landscape that hides the impact and legacy of colonialism and Canada's and British Columbia's dark history of suppression of Indigenous cultures and, until only recently, the refusal to recognize Indigenous nations' rights to their traditional territories and their legal orders.</p>
    <p>This colonial history, its impact and continuing legacy, and the struggle by Indigenous peoples for the legal and political recognition of their rights are issues that lie at the heart of the seminars I have taught on Aboriginal and Treaty Rights, Penal Policy and Criminal Justice. That history of resistance and resilience is one that the projects in the archive have engaged with and animated.</p>

    <h2>Student Voices: Indigenous and Settler Perspectives</h2>
    <p>The archive features projects in which students have reflected on their personal, family and community histories and their intersection with themes in the seminars. Across a broad spectrum of media, both Indigenous and non-Indigenous students have explored the personal, political and legal dimensions of the history of Indigenous-Settler relationships in Canada. There are also projects completed by international exchange students at the Law School that offer visual and textual comparative experiences of how courts and governments in Australia and New Zealand/Aotearoa have addressed issues of the rights of Indigenous peoples.</p>
    <p>The work of conceptualizing and completing their projects has allowed students to express their Indigenous — First Nation and Métis — and Settler identities and experiences in a way that was not otherwise available to them in law school. In many cases their project was the last work they completed in their three years of law school and its presentation to other members of the seminar was an important rite of passage. I should note that the Indigenous people of Canada also include the Inuit. Although I have been privileged to work with Inuit communities as a lawyer, there were no Inuit students in my seminars who presented mixed media projects.</p>

    <h2>How the Archive is Organized</h2>
    <p>The archive is divided into three parts. The first part focuses on a broad spectrum of issues including the five-centuries-old debate on the legal basis for Indigenous Rights, the common law jurisprudence on the nature of these rights, and the significance of their recognition in section 35 of the 1982 Constitution Act. Many projects explore the rhetoric and reality of the application of principles that lie at the heart of the Supreme Court jurisprudence, the importance of considering the Indigenous perspective of the rights in issue, including Indigenous laws, and the role of the reconciliation imperative in understanding the relationship between pre-existing Indigenous sovereignty and asserted Crown sovereignty.</p>
    <p>The second part addresses the history, significance and interpretation of treaty-making. Several projects physically reproduce the ceremonial and diplomatic instruments that were an integral part of early treaty-making; others provide annotated and illustrated commentaries on historical treaties concluded in the 18th and 19th centuries and modern treaties concluded in British Columbia in the 20th and 21st centuries. There are projects by students who are themselves citizens of Indigenous treaty nations that incorporate family and community histories; others by non-Indigenous students that reflect on their experience as non-Indigenous persons growing up in parts of Canada where treaties have been signed.</p>
    <p>The third part explores human rights issues flowing from imprisonment. Since the inception of the penitentiary as a tool of punishment in 18th-century Europe and its adoption in the US and Canada in the 19th century, the human rights of prisoners were viewed as "beyond the ken of the courts." Paralleling the historic absence of the rule of law inside the walls, with the exception of exceptional events like riots, the state of Canadian prisons has fallen far below the horizon of public gaze. Through their creative work students in the Penal Policy Seminar have opened their own minds to the contemporary realities of imprisonment and, in sharing it through the archive, opened windows for the rest of us.</p>
    <p>These realities are not monolithic: Indigenous prisoners, whose overrepresentation in the prisons of our country has been described by the Supreme Court of Canada as "a staggering injustice" — and for this generation represents a replication of what the residential school system did to their parents and grandparents; women experience prison differently, particularly those who are separated from their children; prisoners who experience long periods in solitary confinement suffer what is now recognized by both international human rights standards and Canadian courts as torture and cruel or unusual punishment. The projects communicate across an artistic spectrum the experience of the imprisoned, allowing the listener, viewer, and reader to connect to realities that lie hidden behind wire fences and high walls.</p>

    <h2>Scope and Limitations</h2>
    <p>The archive, although broad and deep in scope, is not presented as a comprehensive or complete analysis of the state of Indigenous and Prisoners' Rights. In my seminars many students chose the more traditional format of writing essays and commentaries on the jurisprudence, particularly on the important and exciting emergence of contemporary international human rights law with the UN Declaration of the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP) and its incorporation into Canadian law through both federal and provincial legislation. Many parts of these essays have found their way into legal arguments influencing the decisions of both Courts of Appeal and the Supreme Court of Canada, and while they represent critical legal thinking by students at the beginning of their legal careers, they make no claim to the artistic genre that the archive presents.</p>
    <p>Given that the projects cover over a quarter century of work, some of the analysis in particular projects reflects the state of the law at the time they were presented. Where there have been later developments in the jurisprudence and legislation I have through both footnotes and commentary provided updated information, but I would emphasize that the archive makes no claim to be, nor should it be relied upon as, a contemporary statement of law.</p>

    <h2>The Creation of Bearing Witness</h2>
    <p>The idea of a publicly accessible archive of law students' artistic interpretations and critiques of the law in projects for my seminars has long been my goal. Its realization has come through the contributions and encouragement of Patrick Long, who has designed and imagined the site to reach beyond the original audience of legal education — students, teachers, and members of the legal profession — and invite a wider public: those interested in human rights, particularly the rights of Indigenous peoples and Prisoners, and those curious about how artistic expression can open windows into the world of law.</p>
    <p>I am also indebted to David Khang, a participant in my seminar on Aboriginal and Treaty Rights Litigation. In addition to his own project in the archive, David worked with me beginning in 2020, at the onset of the COVID-19 lockdown at the Allard Law School, in assembling and photographing the projects selected for the archive. David, an accomplished performance artist, in addition to his photo documentation, was able to provide a critical lens in determining how best to present the projects and has continued to help with their online visualization.</p>
    <p>As a preview of the archive, we show here photos of some of the projects assembled for the first time in one room during their documentation, and some projects on display in Professor Jackson's office at the Law School.</p>

